[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] In multithreaded computer programming, **asynchronous method invocation** (**AMI**), also known as **asynchronous method calls** or the **asynchronous pattern** is a design pattern in which the call site is not blocked while waiting for the called code to finish.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] Instead, the calling thread is notified when the reply arrives.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] Polling for a reply is an undesired option.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] In most programming languages a called method is executed synchronously, i.e. in the thread of execution from which it is invoked.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] If the method takes a long time to complete, e.g. because it is loading data over the internet, the calling thread is blocked until the method has finished.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] When this is not desired, it is possible to start a "worker thread" and invoke the method from there.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] In most programming environments this requires many lines of code, especially if care is taken to avoid the overhead that may be caused by creating many threads.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] AMI solves this problem in that it augments a potentially long-running ("synchronous") object method with an "asynchronous" variant that returns immediately, along with additional methods that make it easy to receive notification of completion, or to wait for completion at a later time.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] One common use of AMI is in the active object design pattern.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] Alternatives are synchronous method invocation and future objects.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] An example for an application that may make use of AMI is a web browser that needs to display a web page even before all images are loaded.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] Since method is a special case of procedure, **asynchronous method invocation** is a special case of asynchronous procedure call.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] FutureTask class in Java use events to solve the same problem.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] This pattern is a variant of AMI whose implementation carries more overhead, but it is useful for objects representing software components.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] The following example is loosely based on a standard AMI style used in the .NET Framework.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] Upon calling `BeginAccomplish`, the client immediately receives an object of type `AsyncResult` (which implements the `IAsyncResult` interface), so it can continue the calling thread with unrelated work.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] In the simplest case, eventually there is no more such work, and the client calls `EndAccomplish` (passing the previously received object), which blocks until the method has completed and the result is available.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] One can also pass a callback method to `BeginAccomplish`, to be invoked when the long-running method completes.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] It typically calls `EndAccomplish` to obtain the return value of the long-running method.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] A problem with the callback mechanism is that the callback function is naturally executed in the worker thread (rather than in the original calling thread), which may cause race conditions.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] In the .NET Framework documentation, the term event-based asynchronous pattern refers to an alternative API style (available since .NET 2.0) using a method named `AccomplishAsync` instead of `BeginAccomplish`.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] A superficial difference is that in this style the return value of the long-running method is passed directly to the callback method.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] Much more importantly, the API uses a special mechanism to run the callback method (which resides in an event object of type `AccomplishCompleted`) in the same thread in which `BeginAccomplish` was called.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/asynchronous-method-invocation] This eliminates the danger of race conditions, making the API easier to use and suitable for software components; on the other hand this implementation of the pattern comes with additional object creation and synchronization overhead.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] An exponential backoff algorithm is a form of closed-loop control system that reduces the rate of a controlled process in response to adverse events.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For example, if a mobile app fails to connect to its server, the mobile app might try again 1 second later, then if it fails again, 2 seconds later, then 4, etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Each time, the pause is multiplied by a fixed amount (in this case, 2).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In this case, the adverse event is failing to connect to the server.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Other examples of adverse events include collisions of network traffic, packet loss, an error response from a service, or an explicit request to reduce the rate (i.e., *back off*).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Here, *t* is the time delay applied between actions, *b* is the multiplicative factor or *base*, and *c* is the number of adverse events observed.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Alternatively, *f* is the frequency (or rate) of the process (i.e., number of actions per unit of time).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The value of *c* is incremented each time an adverse event is observed, leading to an exponential rise in delay and, therefore, an inversely proportionate rate.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] An exponential backoff algorithm where *b* = 2 is referred to as a *binary* exponential backoff algorithm.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] When the rate has been reduced in response to an adverse event, it usually does not remain at that reduced level forever.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] If no adverse events are observed for some period of time, often referred to as the *recovery time* or *cooling-off period*, the rate may be increased again.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The time period that must elapse before attempting to increase the rate again may, itself, be determined by an exponential backoff algorithm.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Typically, recovery of the rate occurs more slowly than reduction of the rate due to backoff and often requires careful tuning to avoid oscillation of the rate.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The exact recovery behaviour is implementation-specific and may be informed by any number of environmental factors.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The mechanism by which rate reduction is achieved in a system may be more complex than a simple time delay.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In some cases, the value *t* may refer to an upper bound on the time delay, rather than a specific time delay value.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The name *exponential backoff* refers to the exponential growth characteristic of the backoff, rather than an exact numeric relationship between adverse event counts and delay times.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Exponential backoff is commonly utilised as part of rate limiting mechanisms in computer systems such as web services, to help enforce fair distribution of access to resources and prevent network congestion.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Each time a service informs a client that it is sending requests too frequently, the client reduces its rate by some predetermined factor until the client's request rate reaches an acceptable equilibrium.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The service may enforce rate limiting by refusing to respond to requests when the client is sending them too frequently, so that misbehaving clients are not allowed to exceed their allotted resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] A benefit of utilising an exponential backoff algorithm over a fixed rate limit is that rate limits through exponential backoff can be achieved dynamically without providing any prior information to the client.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In the event that resources are unexpectedly constrained, e.g., due to heavy load or a service disruption, backoff requests and error responses from the service can automatically decrease the request rate from clients.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] This can help maintain some level of availability rather than overloading the service.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In addition, quality of service can be prioritised to certain clients based on their individual importance, e.g., by reducing the backoff for emergency calls on a telephone network during periods of high load.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In a simple version of the algorithm, messages are delayed by a predetermined (non-random) time.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For example, in SIP protocol over unreliable transport (such as UDP) the client retransmits requests at an interval that starts at T1 seconds (usually 500 ms, which is the estimate of the round-trip time) and doubles after every retransmission until it reaches T2 seconds (which defaults to 4 s).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] This results in retransmission intervals of 500 ms, 1 s, 2 s, 4 s, 4 s then 4 s.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Exponential backoff algorithms can be used to avoid network collisions.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In a point-to-multipoint or statistical time-division multiplexed network, multiple senders communicate over a single shared channel.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] If two senders attempt to transmit a message at the same time, or *talk over* each other, a collision occurs and the messages are damaged or lost.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Each sender can then back off before attempting to retransmit the same message again.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] A deterministic exponential backoff algorithm is unsuitable for this use case since each sender would back off for the same time period, leading them to retransmit simultaneously and cause another collision.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Instead, for purposes of collision avoidance, the time between retransmissions is randomized and the exponential backoff algorithm sets the *range* of delay values that are possible.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The time delay is usually measured in slots, which are fixed-length periods of time on the network.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In a binary exponential backoff algorithm (i.e., one where $b=2$ ), after c collisions, each retransmission is delayed by a random number of slot times between 0 and $2^{c}-1$ .
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] After the first collision, each sender will wait 0 or 1 slot times.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] After the second collision, the senders will wait anywhere from 0 to 3 slot times (inclusive).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] After the third collision, the senders will wait anywhere from 0 to 7 slot times (inclusive), and so forth.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] As the number of retransmission attempts increases, the number of possibilities for delay increases exponentially.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] This decreases the probability of a collision but increases the average latency.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In Ethernet networks, the algorithm is commonly used to schedule retransmissions after collisions.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The retransmission is delayed by an amount of time derived from the slot time (for example, the time it takes to send 512 bits; i.e., 512 bit-times) and the number of attempts to retransmit.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] This example is from the Ethernet protocol, where a sending host is able to know when a collision has occurred (that is, another host has tried to transmit), when it is sending a frame.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] If both hosts attempted to re-transmit as soon as a collision occurred, there would be yet another collision — and the pattern would continue forever.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The hosts must choose a random value within an acceptable range to ensure that this situation doesn't happen.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] An exponential backoff algorithm is therefore used.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The value 51.2 μs is used as an example here because it is the slot time for a 10 Mbit/s Ethernet line.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] However, 51.2 μs could be replaced by any positive value, in practice.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Resend a frame after either 0 seconds or 51.2 μs, chosen at random.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] If that fails, resend the frame after either 0 s, 51.2 μs, 102.4 μs, or 153.6 μs.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] If that still fails, resend the frame after k · 51.2 μs, where k is a random integer between 0 and 23 − 1.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For further failures, after the *c*th failed attempt, resend the frame after k · 51.2 μs, where k is a random integer between 0 and 2*c* − 1.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In a seminal paper published in AFIPS 1970, Norman Abramson presented the idea of multiple users, on different islands, sharing a single radio channel (i.e., a single frequency) to access the main computer at the University of Hawaii without any time synchronization.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Packet collisions at the receiver of the main computer are treated by senders after a timeout as detected errors.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Each sender not receiving a positive acknowledgement from the main computer would retransmit its lost packet.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Abramson assumed that the sequence of packets transmitted into the shared channel is a Poisson process at rate G, which is the sum of the rate S of new packet arrivals to senders and the rate of retransmitted packets into the channel.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Assuming steady state, he showed that the channel throughput rate is $S=Ge^{-2G}$ with a maximum value of 1/(2e) = 0.184 in theory.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Larry Roberts considered a time-slotted ALOHA channel with each time slot long enough for a packet transmission time.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] (A satellite channel using the TDMA protocol is time slotted.) Using the same Poisson process and steady state assumptions as Abramson, Larry Roberts showed that the maximum throughput rate is 1/e = 0.368 in theory.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Roberts was the program manager of the ARPANET research project.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Inspired by the slotted ALOHA idea, Roberts initiated a new ARPANET Satellite System (ASS) project to include satellite links in the ARPANET.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Simulation results by Abramson, his colleagues, and others showed that an ALOHA channel, slotted or not, is unstable and would sometimes go into congestion collapse.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] How much time until congestion collapse depended on the arrival rate of new packets as well as other unknown factors.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In 1971, Larry Roberts asked Professor Leonard Kleinrock and his Ph.D. student, Simon Lam, at UCLA to join the Satellite System project of ARPANET.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Simon Lam would work on the stability, performance evaluation, and adaptive control of slotted ALOHA for his Ph.D. dissertation research.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The first paper he co-authored with Kleinrock was ARPANET Satellite System (ASS) Note 12 disseminated to the ASS group in August 1972.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In this paper, a slot chosen randomly over an interval of K slots was used for retransmission.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] A new result from the model is that increasing K increases channel throughput, which converges to 1/e as K increases to infinity.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] This model retained the assumptions of Poisson arrivals and steady state and was not intended for understanding statistical behaviour and congestion collapse.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] To understand stability, Lam created a discrete-time Markov chain model for analyzing the statistical behaviour of slotted ALOHA in chapter 5 of his dissertation.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The model has three parameters: *N*, *s*, and *p*.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] At any time, each user may be idle or blocked.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Each user has at most one packet to transmit in the next time slot.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] An idle user generates a new packet with probability *s* and transmits it in the next time slot immediately.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] A blocked user transmits its backlogged packet with probability *p*, where 1/*p* = (*K*+1)/2 to keep the average retransmission interval the same.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The throughput-delay results of the two retransmission methods were compared by extensive simulations and found to be essentially the same.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Lam’s model provides mathematically rigorous answers to the stability questions of slotted ALOHA, as well as an efficient algorithm for computing the throughput-delay performance for any stable system.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For slotted ALOHA with a finite *N* and a finite *K*, the Markov chain model can be used to determine whether the system is stable or unstable for a given input rate (*N*×*s*) and, if it is stable, compute its average packet delay and channel throughput rate.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Increasing *K* increases the maximum number of users that can be accommodated by a stable slotted ALOHA channel.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For a finite (*N* × *s*), an unstable channel for the current *K* value can be made stable by increasing *K* to a sufficiently large value, to be referred to as its *K*(*N*,*s*).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Lam used Markov decision theory and developed optimal control policies for slotted ALOHA, but these policies require all blocked users to know the current state (number of blocked users) of the Markov chain.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In 1973, Lam decided that instead of using a complex protocol for users to estimate the system state, he would create a simple algorithm for each user to use its own local information, i.e., the number of collisions its backlogged packet has encountered.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Applying the above Corollary, Lam invented the following class of adaptive backoff algorithms (named Heuristic RCP).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] A Heuristic RCP algorithm consists of the following steps: (1) Let *m* denote the number of previous collisions incurred by a packet at a user as the feedback information in its control loop.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For a new packet, *K*(0) is initialized to 1.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] (2) The packet’s retransmission interval *K*(*m*) increases as *m* increases (until the channel becomes stable, as implied by the above Corollary).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For implementation, with *K*(0)=1, as m increases, *K*(*m*) can be increased by multiplication (or by addition).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Binary Exponential Backoff (BEB) used in Ethernet several years later is a special case of Heuristic RCP with $K(m)=2^{m}$ .
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] It is, however, not optimal for many applications because BEB uses 2 as the only multiplier, which provides no flexibility for optimization.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In particular, for a system with a large number of users, BEB increases *K*(*m*) too slowly.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] On the other hand, for a system with a small number of users, a fairly small *K* is sufficient for the system to be stable, and backoff would not be necessary.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] To illustrate an example of a multiplicative RCP that uses several multipliers, see the bottom row in Table 6.3 on page 214 in Chapter 6 of Lam’s dissertation, or the bottom row in Table III on page 902 in the Lam-Kleinrock paper.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For a packet with 1 previous collision, *K*(1) = *K*(0) × 10 = 10 (The multiplier jumps up directly to *K** = 10 which was found to be the optimum *K* value at steady state for this particular system (slotted ALOHA for a satellite channel).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For a packet with 2 previous collisions, *K*(2) = *K*(1) × 10 = 100 (one more collision, *K* jumps up 10 times).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For this example, *K*=200 is sufficient for a stable slotted ALOHA system with *N* equal to about 400, which follows from result 3 above Corollary.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] There is no need to increase *K* any further.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The 'truncated' variant of the algorithm introduces a limit on *c*.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] This simply means that after a certain number of increases, the exponentiation stops.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Without a limit on *c*, the delay between transmissions may become undesirably long if a sender repeatedly observes adverse events, e.g., due to a degradation in network performance.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] In a randomized system, this may occur by chance, leading to unpredictable latency; longer delays due to unbounded increases in *c* are exponentially less probable, but they are effectively inevitable on a busy network due to the law of truly large numbers.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Limiting *c* helps to reduce the possibility of unexpectedly long transmission latencies and improve recovery times after a transient outage.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] For example, if the ceiling is set at *i* = 10 in a truncated binary exponential backoff algorithm, (as it is in the IEEE 802.3 CSMA/CD standard), then the maximum delay is 1023 slot times, i.e.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Selecting an appropriate backoff limit for a system involves striking a balance between collision probability and latency.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] By increasing the ceiling, there is an exponential reduction in the probability of collision on each transmission attempt.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] At the same time, increasing the limit also exponentially increases the range of possible latency times for a transmission, leading to less deterministic performance and an increase in the average latency.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] The optimal limit value for a system is specific to both the implementation and environment.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] Given a uniform distribution of backoff times, the expected backoff time is the mean of the possibilities.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/exponential-backoff] which is, for the example, *E*(3) = 3.5 slots.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/job-queue] In system software, a **job queue** (a.k.a.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/job-queue] **batch queue**, **input queue**), is a data structure maintained by job scheduler software containing jobs to run.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/job-queue] Users submit their programs that they want executed, "jobs", to the queue for batch processing.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/job-queue] The scheduler software maintains the queue as the pool of jobs available for it to run.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/job-queue] Any process that comes to the CPU should wait in a queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] In computing, the **producer-consumer problem** (also known as the **bounded-buffer problem**) is a family of problems described by Edsger W.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra wrote about the unbounded buffer case: "We consider two processes, which are called the 'producer' and the 'consumer' respectively.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The producer is a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle it produces a certain portion of information, that has to be processed by the consumer.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The consumer is also a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle, it can process the next portion of information, as has been produced by the producer ...
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] He wrote about the bounded buffer case: "We have studied a producer and a consumer coupled via a buffer with unbounded capacity ...
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] And about the multiple producer-consumer case: "We consider a number of producer/consumer pairs, where pairi is coupled via an information stream containing ni portions.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen and Niklaus Wirth saw soon the problem of semaphores: "I have come to the same conclusion with regard to semaphores, namely that they are not suitable for higher level languages.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The original semaphore bounded buffer solution was written in ALGOL style.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The buffer can store N portions or elements.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The "number of queueing portions" semaphore counts the filled locations in the buffer, the "number of empty positions" semaphore counts the empty locations in the buffer and the semaphore "buffer manipulation" works as mutex for the buffer put and get operations.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is full, that is the number of empty positions is zero, the producer thread will wait in the P(number of empty positions) operation.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is empty, that is the number of queueing portions is zero, the consumer thread will wait in the P(number of queueing portions) operation.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operations release the semaphores.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] As a side effect, a thread can move from the wait queue to the ready queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The P() operation decreases the semaphore value down to zero.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operation increases the semaphore value.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] As of C++ 20, semaphores are part of the language.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra's solution can easily be written in modern C++.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The variable buffer_manipulation is a mutex.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The semaphore feature of acquiring in one thread and releasing in another thread is not needed.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The lock_guard() statement instead of a lock() and unlock() pair is C++ RAII.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The lock_guard destructor ensures lock release in case of an exception.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] This solution can handle multiple consumer threads and/or multiple producer threads.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen defined the monitor: I will use the term monitor to denote a shared variable and the set of meaningful operations on it.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The purpose of a monitor is to control the scheduling of resources among individual processes according to a certain policy.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] Tony Hoare laid a theoretical foundation for the monitor.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor is an object that contains variables `buffer`, `head`, `tail` and `count` to realize a circular buffer, the condition variables `nonempty` and `nonfull` for synchronization and the methods `append` and `remove` to access the bounded buffer.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor operation wait corresponds to the semaphore operation P or acquire, signal corresponds to V or release.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The circled operation (+) are taken modulo N.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The presented Pascal style pseudo code shows a Hoare monitor.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] A Mesa monitor uses `while count` instead of `if count`.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The C++ version needs an additional mutex for technical reasons.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] It uses assert to enforce the preconditions for the buffer add and remove operations.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The very first producer-consumer solution in the Electrologica computers used 'channels'.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] Hoare defined channels: An alternative to explicit naming of source and destination would be to name a port through which communication is to take place.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The port names would be local to the processes, and the manner in which pairs of ports are to be connected by channels could be declared in the head of a parallel command.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] Brinch Hansen implemented channels in the programming languages Joyce and Super Pascal.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The Plan 9 operating system programming language Alef, the Inferno operating system programming language Limbo have channels.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The program entry point is at function `threadmain`.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The function call `ch = chancreate(sizeof(ulong), 1)` creates the channel, the function call `sendul(ch, i)` sends a value into the channel and the function call `p = recvul(ch)` receives a value from the channel.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The programming language Go has channels, too.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The Go producer-consumer solution uses the main Go routine for consumer and creates a new, unnamed Go routine for the producer.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The two Go routines are connected with channel ch.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] This channel can queue up to three int values.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The statement `ch := make(chan int, 3)` creates the channel, the statement `ch <- produceMessage()` sends a value into the channel and the statement `recvMsg := range ch` receives a value from the channel.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The allocation of memory resources, the allocation of processing resources, and the synchronization of resources are done by the programming language automatically.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] Leslie Lamport documented a bounded buffer producer-consumer solution for one producer and one consumer: We assume that the buffer can hold at most b messages, b >= 1.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] In our solution, we let k be a constant greater than b, and let s and r be integer variables assuming values between 0 and k-1.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] We assume that initially s=r and the buffer is empty.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] By choosing k to be a multiple of b, the buffer can be implemented as an array B [0: b - 1].
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The producer simply puts each new message into B[s mod b], and the consumer takes each message from B[r mod b].
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The algorithm is shown below, generalized for infinite k.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The Lamport solution uses busy waiting in the thread instead of waiting in the scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] This solution neglects the impact of scheduler thread switch at inconvenient times.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] If the first thread has read a variable value from memory, the scheduler switches to the second thread that changes the variable value, and the scheduler switches back to the first thread then the first thread uses the old value of the variable, not the current value.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] Atomic read-modify-write solves this problem.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] Modern C++ offers `atomic` variables and operations for multi-thread programming.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The following busy waiting C++11 solution for one producer and one consumer uses atomic read-modify-write operations `fetch_add` and `fetch_sub` on the atomic variable `count`.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The circular buffer index variables `head` and `tail` are thread-local and therefore not relevant for memory consistency.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/producer-consumer-problem] The variable `count` controls the busy waiting of the producer and consumer thread.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] In computing, a **task** is a unit of execution or a unit of work.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] The term is ambiguous; precise alternative terms include *process*, light-weight process, *thread* (for execution), *step*, *request*, or *query* (for work).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] In the adjacent diagram, there are queues of incoming work to do and outgoing completed work, and a thread pool of threads to perform this work.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] Either the work units themselves or the threads that perform the work can be referred to as "tasks", and these can be referred to respectively as requests/responses/threads, incoming tasks/completed tasks/threads (as illustrated), or requests/responses/tasks.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] In the sense of "unit of execution", in some operating systems, a task is synonymous with a process, and in others with a thread.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] In non-interactive execution (batch processing), a task is a unit of execution within a job, with the task itself typically a process.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] The term "multitasking" primarily refers to the processing sense – multiple tasks *executing* at the same time – but has nuances of the work sense of multiple tasks being *performed* at the same time.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] In online systems, tasks most commonly correspond to a single *request* (in request–response architectures) or a *query* (in information retrieval), either a single stage of handling, or the whole system-wide handling.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] The term task in OS/360 through z/OS is roughly equivalent to light-weight process; the tasks in a job step share an address space.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] However, in MVS/ESA through z/OS, a task or Service Request Block (SRB) may have access to other address spaces via its access list.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] The term *task* is used in the Linux kernel (at least since v2.6.13, up to and including v4.8) to refer to a unit of execution, which may share various system resources with other tasks on the system.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] Depending on the level of sharing, the task may be regarded as a conventional thread or process.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] Tasks are brought into existence using the `clone()` system call, where a user can specify the desired level of resource sharing.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] The term was popularized with the introduction of OS/360 (announced 1964), which featured Multiprogramming with a Fixed number of Tasks (MFT) and Multiprogramming with a Variable number of Tasks (MVT).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] In this case tasks were identified with light-weight processes, a job consisted of a number of tasks, and, later, tasks could have sub-tasks (in modern terminology, child processes).
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] Today the term "task" is used very ambiguously.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] For example, the Windows Task Manager manages (running) *processes*, while Windows Task Scheduler schedules *programs* to execute in future, what is traditionally known as a job scheduler, and uses the `.job` extension.
[src:gcp-cloud-tasks/task-computing] By contrast, the term "task queue" is commonly used in the sense of "units of work".
